                <tr> 
                  <td colspan="4"><p><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">Additional 
                      notes</font></p>
                    <ul>
                      <li><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">Parablastoidea 
                        are small class of primitive blastozoan echinoderms containing 
                        three genera found in the early Middle Ordovician</font></li>
                      <li><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">The 
                        Ophiuroids or brittle stars are probably the most common 
                        extant echinoderms. They occur in large numbers in all 
                        parts of the oceans, from the shallowest coastal waters 
                        to the deep sea trenches.</font></li>
                      <li><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">Blastoids 
                        persisted until their extinction at the end of Permian, 
                        some 250 million years ago. Although never as diverse 
                        as the crinoids, blastoids are prodigious as fossils, 
                        especially from the Carboniferous, and are particularly 
                        abundant in some U.S. midwestern states.</font></li>
                      <li><font size="2" face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica, sans-serif">Crinoidea 
                        has more than 1000 genera, with some 80 extant species.</font></li>
                    </ul></td>
                </tr>
